description: From Middle English overleden, from Old English oferlǣdan (“to oppress, translate”), equivalent to over- +‎ lead.

verbs.description: overlead (third-person singular simple present overleads, present participle overleading, simple past and past participle overled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To lead excessively or too much.
examples: If you overlead this question with too binding absoluteness requirements I am afraid that a satisfactory and not dogmatic answer will be rather difficult to find.

entries.meaning: (transitive, obsolete) To dominate; domineer over; oppress.
examples: I believe it well, false recreant knight, said Sir Gawaine, for thou hast many long days overled me, and us all, and destroyed many of our good knights.

entries.meaning: (transitive, obsolete) To affront; treat with indignity.
